\paragraph{The observation is conditioned on the specific scale choices.} The selection of charm as the only varied quark is motivated by the sign of the required correction and by the absence of alternative scales for top and bottom that move $Q$ toward $2/3$. This is a physically transparent but post-hoc choice; we do not present it as a pre-registered test.

\paragraph{The residual lies within input uncertainty.} The residual of $+5.10\times10^{-5}$ is smaller than $\sigma_Q$, so the result is compatible with $Q = 2/3$ exactly, but also with a range of other values. No statistical significance is claimed.

\paragraph{Not a derivation or mechanism.} We have not derived the relation from a Lagrangian or symmetry. The inputs were all known before this calculation. We offer no mechanism.

\paragraph{$\overline{\text{MS}}$-specific.} The result uses the $\overline{\text{MS}}$ scheme. Robustness across alternative heavy-quark mass schemes (1S, PS, MSR, kinetic) has not been tested.

\section{Discussion}

The companion paper \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} reported that the squared outer Soddy curvature of the lepton triple matches $m_s^{\overline{\text{MS}}}$ at the lepton-sum scale $\Sigma m_\ell$. The present note finds that for the heavy $(c,b,t)$ Koide combination, evaluating $m_c$ at $m_\tau$ brings $Q$ to within $5\times10^{-5}$ of $2/3$, while the other natural charm-scale alternative ($\Sigma m_\ell$) gives a residual two orders of magnitude larger. The two observations involve different lepton-derived scales ($\Sigma m_\ell$ for strange, $m_\tau$ for charm) and different algebraic structures (Soddy curvature vs. Koide combination). 

Whether this pattern is accidental or points to an underlying relation is not settled by the present work. The narrowness of the observed near-coincidence (one of three natural charm-scale prescriptions, with the other two giving residuals orders of magnitude larger) is a numerical fact; its interpretation is left to future theoretical investigation.

\section*{Computational note}

All computations are reproducible from the accompanying GitHub repository \citep{RepoHeavy}. Four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ running is performed via \texttt{CRunDec} \citep{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$ and full threshold matching at $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(m_b)$, and $m_t(m_t)$. Total runtime is under one minute.

